    <title>Fail to Get the Access while Using 2FA in Github</title>
    <link href="http://lancegin.cc/tech/fail-to-get-the-access-while-using-2FA-in-Github/"/>
    <id>http://lancegin.cc/tech/fail-to-get-the-access-while-using-2FA-in-Github/</id>
    <published>2015-09-13T03:55:31.000Z</published>
    <updated>2017-08-27T05:13:39.000Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Nowadays, Github set a 2-factor authentication, that means if you want to login or push some codes to your repo by HTTPS, you should input 2 keys to authenticate yourself.</p>
<p>But the version of Git has not caught the step of Github, if you push codes to your repo in terminal by Git, it will never let you go.</p>
<p><img src="http://outub9z8v.bkt.clouddn.com/2fa_01.png" alt=""></p>
<p>The problem bordered me harder, and today I found a way to solve it. We can use an access token to ignore the 2FA.</p>
<p>• first you can go to the setting page to find the button to generate an access token</p>
<p><img src="http://outub9z8v.bkt.clouddn.com/2fa_02.png" alt=""></p>
<p>• then make sure the <code>repo:status</code> has been checked</p>
<p><img src="http://outub9z8v.bkt.clouddn.com/2fa_03.png" alt=""></p>
<p>• now you will see your new access token that will be used to ignore the 2FA.</p>
<p>• from then on, while you want to push or pull codes from your repo, you should tap <code>git config --global credential.helper store</code> first, then tap your username and your new access token.</p>
<p>Then the 2FA problem will not border you anymore. And, your Github will be safer.</p>
]]></content>
    
